++      "content": "A 2024 meta-analysis in Nature Human Behaviour reviewed 106 studies of human-AI collaboration across 370 effect sizes. The headline finding: on average, the human-AI combination performed worse than the better of the two working alone. The team (Vaccaro, Almaatouq, and Malone at MIT) concluded that adding a human reviewer often degraded the output.\n\nThe result is counterintuitive. A person added to an AI workflow should at least match the AI's solo output, because the person can override obvious errors. The data says otherwise. Most studies in the meta-analysis showed combinations losing ground to the stronger party alone. Decision tasks (medical triage, classification, forecasting) showed the largest deficits. Content creation tasks were the one area where the combination delivered reliable gains.\n\nThe Discernment lesson sits inside this finding. Combination underperforms when the human's judgment is poorly calibrated. Reviewers reject correct AI outputs, accept wrong ones, or anchor on the AI's draft instead of independently evaluating it. AI capability is fixed in any given session. Your judgment is the variable that determines whether the combination beats either alone. The training that closes the gap is calibration.\n\nThat is what Week 4 of the pilot is testing. The challenge to share Claude-assisted work with a colleague before Friday is calibration practice. Two readers will catch what one missed. Shared standards travel between people. The colleague who tells you 'this doesn't sound like you' is doing the work the meta-analysis says most human reviewers fail at.",
